It took more than two years, but some big Wall Street
banks=E2=80=94along with several of their European and Japanese counterpart=
s=E2=80=94are finally breathing a sigh of relief now that nearly $9 billion=
 of the $13 billion of X debt they=E2=80=99ve been holding on to is flying =
out the door. Incredibly, the debt is being priced close to par, which is s=
urely assuaging the banks=E2=80=99 regulators and credit committees. Of cou=
rse, this is quite a turnaround from the early days of Elon Musk=E2=80=99s =
$44 billion acquisition of the company, when he was busy firing
75 percent of Twitter=E2=80=99s employees and telling Bob Iger to go fuck h=
imself, and advertisers were fleeing the social media platform in droves.=
=C2=A0

In the end, the banks=E2=80=99 stubbornness has miraculously paid off, as t=
he first-lien X debt=E2=80=94that $9 billion=E2=80=94is finding new homes i=
n the hands of eager buyers and away from the banks=E2=80=99 balance sheets=
=2E It=E2=80=99s an outcome I could not ha=
ve predicted. According to the Fina=
ncial Times, a group of investors
including Diameter Capital Partners, run by Scott Goodwin (the son of my fo=
rmer JPMorgan partner John Goodwin), bought about $1 billion face amount of=
 the X debt in January, at a meaningful discount of about 90 cents on the d=
ollar to generate around a 14 percent yield. That group is already in the m=
oney on the debt, now that it has traded up to around par. Lately, other bu=
yers have had to pay more: A big chunk of the debt sold
for about 97 cents on the dollar in recent weeks, and another $3 billion or=
 so is about to be sold for close to par, or without any discount at all. M=
organ Stanley, for instance, is boosting its X debt offering to $4.7 billio=
n, with no discount offered, because of high demand.

How the heck was this surprise turnaround engineered? That question has bee=
n vexing me for months. In the first 18 months or so after the deal closed,=
 the consensus on Wall Street was that the $31 billion of equity
that Elon and his friends invested in the buyout=E2=80=94$24 billion of whi=
ch came from Elon himself=E2=80=94was a lost cause. The only question left =
was how badly the seven banks that provided the remaining $13 billion, in t=
he form of two tranches of debt, would get burned when they sold it off the=
ir balance sheets, as they=E2=80=99re pretty much required to do by regulat=
ors. There was little hope for much more than 50 to 60 cents on the dollar,=
 even as X was somehow keeping current on its annual $1.4 billion in
interest payments. But I think I=E2=80=99ve finally gotten to the bottom of=
 how it happened, and why the selling banks are now dancing a jig.

The Linda Factor
----------------

Some of the buyers attribute at least part of the turnaround, improbably, t=
o
Linda Yaccarino, whom Elon hired away from NBCU in May 2023 to become X=E2=
=80=99s C.E.O. Since then, she has unveiled a number of subscription-based =
products that seem to be working. She has also, somehow, managed to lure ad=
vertisers back to the platform. (Though she has certainly benefited from th=
e fact that few companies want to pick a fight with Musk these days, given =
his ubiquity, including in the White House.) Meanwhile, X is also benefitin=
g from Meta=E2=80=99s removal of many controls on
its social media platforms, too, offering advertisers a similarly brand-uns=
afe experience. Direct X competitors Threads and Bluesky haven=E2=80=99t qu=
ite cracked the code. TikTok has its own existential crisis, obviously. So =
there aren=E2=80=99t many better options.

