=E2=80=9CCircular Accounting Nonsense=E2=80=9D
----------------------------------

All at once, it seems, the puzzle pieces have come together,
benefiting the big banks and assuring buyers that the $9 billion of X first=
-lien paper is money-good. =E2=80=9CEverything is moving in the right direc=
tion,=E2=80=9D one Wall Street source told me. From a loan-to-value perspec=
tive, which is how buyers look at these opportunities, you=E2=80=99ve got a=
 first-lien loan of $9 billion and a value of $20 billion, just accounting =
for X and its stake in xAI: a 45 percent loan-to-value ratio, giving invest=
ors all the comfort they=E2=80=99d ever need to buy this paper at or close =
to
par.

=C2=A0

That translates to good news for Morgan Stanley, Bank of America, Barclays,=
 Mizuho, MUFG, Soci=C3=A9t=C3=A9 G=C3=A9n=C3=A9rale, and BNP Paribas, who c=
an now move this debt off their balance sheets and make room for the next r=
ound of leveraged loans. There=E2=80=99s still the $4 billion of junior X d=
ebt that will likely remain on their balance sheets for the time being. But=
 they might as well wait and see what happens at this
point, right?

=C2=A0

As for the $31 billion of equity, things seem to be looking up on that fron=
t, too, albeit slowly. Using the $20 billion enterprise valuation, that wou=
ld mean the X equity is now worth around $7 billion (after subtracting the =
$13 billion of debt at par), or 77.5 percent less than the original $31 bil=
lion of equity invested. That pretty much squares with the price that one F=
idelity fund with a
$19.7 million stake in X valued its position as in November: $5.8 million, =
a decrease of 71 percent from the original value of the investment, but up =
from a valuation of $5.5 million in October.

Of course, there are at least a few skeptics of this suddenly rosy scenario=
=2E On Bluesky, Kara Swisher referred t=
o the payments from xAI to X for its d=
ata as =E2=80=9Ccircular accounting nonsense.=E2=80=9D Another source claim=
ed that Elon =E2=80=9Cjust moved money from one pocket
to the other, to make it look profitable so he could sell the debt,=E2=80=
=9D and that user growth is =E2=80=9Cstagnant,=E2=80=9D revenue is =E2=80=
=9Chorrible,=E2=80=9D and Linda is =E2=80=9Ca clown.=E2=80=9D Is this skept=
icism or schadenfreude? I haven=E2=80=99t a clue. But the debt is moving, a=
nd at prices that would=E2=80=99ve seemed implausible six months ago. Regar=
dless of how Elon did it, the debt syndication clearly seems to have worked=
 out for the banks, and for some of the first wave of investors who bought =
that debt.

We=E2=80=99re still far from a payday for Elon=E2=80=99s fellow equity inve=
stors, such as a16z, Larry Ellison, and the Saudi billionaire Prince Alwale=
ed. But between the sale of a majority of the debt for nearly par, the A.I.=
 valuation euphoria, the increasing EBITDA, and the ongoing Elon-Trump brom=
ance (like other media companies, X recently settled its lawsuit with Trump=
 for booting him off the platform, pre-Elon, because of January 6),
the first glimmers of hope in more than two years are starting to emerge fo=
r this deal, once considered one of the worst made after the 2008 financial=
 crisis. I have to admit, I didn=E2=80=99t see that coming.

