=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">It took more than two years, but some big =
Wall Street
banks=E2=80=94along with several of their European and Japanese counterpart=
s=E2=80=94are <em>finally</em> breathing a sigh of relief now that nearly $=
9 billion of the $13 billion of X debt they=E2=80=99ve been holding on to i=
s flying out the door. Incredibly, the debt is being priced close to par, w=
hich is surely assuaging the banks=E2=80=99 regulators and credit committee=
s. Of course, this is quite a turnaround from the early days of <strong>Elo=
n Musk</strong>=E2=80=99s $44 billion acquisition of the company, when he w=
as busy firing
75 percent of Twitter=E2=80=99s employees and telling <strong>Bob Iger </st=
rong>to go fuck himself, and advertisers were fleeing the social media plat=
form in droves.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>In the end, the banks=
=E2=80=99 stubbornness has miraculously paid off, as the first-lien X debt=
=E2=80=94that $9 billion=E2=80=94is finding new homes in the hands of eager=
 buyers and away from the banks=E2=80=99 balance sheets. It=E2=80=99s an ou=
tcome I could not have predicted. According to the <em>Financial Times</em>=
, a group of investors
including Diameter Capital Partners, run by <strong>Scott</strong> <strong>=
Goodwin</strong> (the son of my former JPMorgan partner <strong>John</stron=
g> <strong>Goodwin</strong>), bought about $1 billion face amount of the X =
debt in January, at a meaningful discount of about 90 cents on the dollar t=
o generate around a 14 percent yield. That group is already in the money on=
 the debt, now that it has traded up to around par. Lately, other buyers ha=
ve had to pay more: A big chunk of the debt sold
for about 97 cents on the dollar in recent weeks, and another $3 billion or=
 so is about to be sold for close to par, or without any discount at all. M=
organ Stanley, for instance, is boosting its X debt offering to $4.7 billio=
n, with no discount offered, because of high demand.<br/><br/>How the heck =
was this surprise turnaround engineered? That question has been vexing me f=
or months. In the first 18 months or so after the deal closed, the consensu=
s on Wall Street was that the $31 billion of equity
that Elon and his friends invested in the buyout=E2=80=94$24 billion of whi=
ch came from Elon himself=E2=80=94was a lost cause. The only question left =
was how badly the seven banks that provided the remaining $13 billion, in t=
he form of two tranches of debt, would get burned when they sold it off the=
ir balance sheets, as they=E2=80=99re pretty much required to do by regulat=
ors. There was little hope for much more than 50 to 60 cents on the dollar,=
 even as X was somehow keeping current on its annual $1.4 billion in
interest payments. But I think I=E2=80=99ve finally gotten to the bottom of=
 how it happened, and why the selling banks are now dancing a jig.</p></div=
