bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">All at once, it seems, the puzzle pieces have c=
ome together,
benefiting the big banks and assuring buyers that the $9 billion of X first=
-lien paper is money-good. =E2=80=9CEverything is moving in the right direc=
tion,=E2=80=9D one Wall Street source told me. From a loan-to-value perspec=
tive, which is how buyers look at these opportunities, you=E2=80=99ve got a=
 first-lien loan of $9 billion and a value of $20 billion, just accounting =
for X and its stake in xAI: a 45 percent loan-to-value ratio, giving invest=
ors all the comfort they=E2=80=99d ever need to buy this paper at or close =
to
par.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"marg=
in:0;margin-bottom:0px;">That translates to good news for Morgan Stanley, B=
ank of America, Barclays, Mizuho, MUFG, Soci=C3=A9t=C3=A9 G=C3=A9n=C3=A9ral=
e, and BNP Paribas, who can now move this debt off their balance sheets and=
 make room for the next round of leveraged loans. There=E2=80=99s still the=
 $4 billion of junior X debt that will likely remain on their balance sheet=
s for the time being. But they might as well wait and see what happens at t=
his
point, right?</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">As for the $31 billion of equity, things =
seem to be looking up on that front, too, albeit slowly. Using the $20 bill=
ion enterprise valuation, that would mean the X equity is now worth around =
$7 billion (after subtracting the $13 billion of debt at par), or 77.5 perc=
ent less than the original $31 billion of equity invested. That pretty much=
 squares with the price that one Fidelity fund with a
$19.7 million stake in X valued its position as in November: $5.8 million, =
a decrease of 71 percent from the original value of the investment, but up =
from a valuation of $5.5 million in October.<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Of course, there are at least a few skeptics of thi=
s suddenly rosy scenario. On Bluesky, Kara Swisher referred to the payments=
 from xAI to X for its data as =E2=80=9Ccircular accounting nonsense.=E2=80=
=9D Another source claimed that Elon =E2=80=9Cjust moved money from one poc=
ket
to the other, to make it look profitable so he could sell the debt,=E2=80=
=9D and that user growth is =E2=80=9Cstagnant,=E2=80=9D revenue is =E2=80=
=9Chorrible,=E2=80=9D and Linda is =E2=80=9Ca clown.=E2=80=9D Is this skept=
icism or <em>schadenfreude</em>? I haven=E2=80=99t a clue. But the debt is =
moving, and at prices that would=E2=80=99ve seemed implausible six months a=
go. Regardless of <em>how</em> Elon did it, the debt syndication clearly se=
ems to have worked out for the banks, and for some of the first wave of inv=
estors who bought that debt.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">
<br/>We=E2=80=99re still far from a payday for Elon=E2=80=99s fellow equity=
 investors, such as a16z, <strong>Larry</strong> <strong>Ellison</strong>, =
and the Saudi billionaire <strong>Prince</strong> <strong>Alwaleed</strong>=
=2E But between the sale of a majority=20=
of the debt for nearly par, the A.I. v=
aluation euphoria, the increasing EBITDA, and the ongoing Elon-Trump broman=
ce (like other media companies, X recently settled its lawsuit with Trump f=
or booting him off the platform, pre-Elon, because of January 6),
the first glimmers of hope in more than two years are starting to emerge fo=
r this deal, once considered one of the worst made after the 2008 financial=
 crisis. I have to admit, I didn=E2=80=99t see that coming.</p></div>
